etymologies: early 19th century; earliest use found in Joseph Hunter (1783–1861), antiquary and record scholar. From French pousse dust, powder, rubbish in fine particles, alteration of an apparently unattested Old French form *pous from classical Latin pulvis dust, powder; compare Old Occitan, Occitan pols powder, dust, Catalan pols dust, and also Spanish polvo. Perhaps compare earlier pouse
